    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="edition">
            <ab>
                <lb n="1"/>Μνε͂μα φίλοι με<gap reason="lost" quantity="8" unit="character" precision="medium"/>     
                <lb n="2"/>πατὲρ ἐπέθεκε θανόντ<supplied reason="lost">ι</supplied>
                <lb n="3"/>χσὺν δὲ φίλε μέτερ <space quantity="1" precision="low"></space>
            <lb n="4"/><gap reason="lost" quantity="1" unit="line"/> 
                
            </ab></div>
            
            <div type="translation">
            <p>"the father and dear mother set the monument to the dear late Me[gacles?]"</p></div>

            <div type="commentary">
            <p>One report says that the fragments were found outside Athens, used to line later
                    graves (Richter). The Berlin authorities reported that their fragment area of
                    Anavyssos, near Olympos (Blümel). The artistic and paleographic features suggest
                    dating the monument to the middle of the sixth century BCE. As many epitaphs,
                    the inscription forms an elegiac couplet. Richter has suggested to reconstruct
                    με as Με[γακλεῖ]. If so, the monument was set up in commemoration of Megacles, a
                    member of the Alcmeonid family. Traces of red and black dye on different parts of
                    the monument. </p></div>
            
            <div type="apparatus">
            <p>line 1, Wade-Gery and Raubitsche: Με[γακλεῖ με] | Croenert: μ’ ἐ[πὶ παιδὶ] line 3,
                    Wade-Gery and Raubitsche: φίλε [---] | Croenert: Φ[ανὸ μέτερ, ὄνομα δ’
                    Ἀντιφάνες] </p></div>
            

